## The Physical Principles of the Quantum Theory

This is a book. A rather significant one, if you must know, penned by [Werner Heisenberg](/Werner_Heisenberg), a man whose name is synonymous with the very foundations of our understanding of the minuscule. It’s German, naturally. The original title, *Physikalischen Prinzipien der Quantentheorie*, sounds like a well-placed curse, doesn't it? Published in 1930, a year that feels both impossibly distant and eerily familiar. It was later translated into English by [Carl Eckart](/Carl_Eckart) and [Frank C. Hoyt](/Frank_C._Hoyt), because apparently, some concepts are too fundamental to be confined to a single tongue.

The original German edition was put out by S. Hirzel Verlag. Then the [University of Chicago Press](/University_of_Chicago_Press) decided it was worth bringing to a wider audience. Later, in 1949, [Dover Publications](/Dover_Publications) saw fit to re-release it, claiming it was "unabridged and unaltered." A bold claim, considering how things tend to shift. It’s part of their *Dover books on physics* series, which, if you ask me, sounds like the dusty corner of a forgotten library.

